{
  "text": "Medical imaging technology allows doctors access to portions of the human body which are visually inaccessible to the human eye. Often inspecting these medical images is a labor intensive process performed by diagnostic radiologists. The accuracy of the radiologist is obtained through training and experience [CITATION_1] but even with extensive training and experience there are variations in interpretations and accuracy among radiologists [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Despite an increasing emphasis on evidence-based medicine and improved imaging techniques, quantitative 'gold-standards' and clear guidelines for a radiologist's role in quantitative measurements remain elusive [CITATION_4] . Image processing provides a way of both automating portions of the examination as well as providing standard tools for radiologists to use when reading an image. The qualitative nature of many radiological observations suggests that topological features may be useful in the classification and interpretation of medical images.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "44667721",
